<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-154-850  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 154 850.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  March 20 1989 v15 n6 p68(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The ups and downs of climbing the techno-ladder. (dual ladderpromotion systems for technologists)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Berkman, Barbara N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Parallel ladder promotion schemes are used in many companies toretain and recruit technical staff.andP;  Engineers are allowed to moveupward in a company without taking on managerial responsibilities,and without wasting their special skills and training.andP;  Dualladder programs often have their problems, however.andP;  The systemwas designed to correct inequities in salaries and bonuses, butpower and status generally remain in the hands of the managers.andO;Monetary compensation alone does not always motivate technicalachievement.andP;  Technologists are usually unable to advance higherthan the equivalent of a division general manager, whereas amanager at this level is not stopped until he reaches thepresidency of the company.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Personnel managementPromotion of EmployeeComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>